nodd\" clip-rule=\"evenodd\" d=\"M16 11a5 5 0 0 1-5 5H5a5 5 0 0 1-5-5V5a5 5 0 0 1 5-5h6a5 5 0 0 1 5 5v6zm-4.5-2.5h2v-6h-6v2h4v4zm-9-1h2v4h4v2h-6v-6z\"></path></svg>Click to enlarge</button></span> <h2 class=\"paywall-full-content\">Commentary as of 12/31/24</h2> <ul class=\"paywall-full-content\"> <li>The fund posted a return of 1.83% (Class I shares) for the fourth quarter of 2024.</li> <li>The fund underperformed its benchmark during the quarter, though it delivered a positive performance for the full year. During the quarter, fundamental measures drove unsuccessful security selection that struggled around the U.S. election outcome. Certain sentiment measures also detracted.</li> <li>From a sector-positioning perspective, the fund remained largely neutral. However, there were slight overweight allocations to the industrials and information technology (IT) sectors, and slight underweight exposures to the energy and consumer staples sectors.</li> </ul> <h2 class=\"paywall-full-content\">Top 10 holdings (%)</h2> <span class=\"table-responsive paywall-full-content\"><span class=\"table-scroll-wrapper\"><span data-intersection-boundary=\"start\"></span><table> <colgroup> <col> <col> </colgroup> <tr> <td>Apple (<a href=\"https://seekingalpha.com/symbol/AAPL\" title=\"Apple Inc.\">AAPL</a>)</td> <td>7.50</td> </tr> <tr> <td>Microsoft (<a href=\"https://seekingalpha.com/symbol/MSFT\" title=\"Microsoft Corporation\">MSFT</a>)</td> <td>6.90</td> </tr> <tr> <td>Nvidia Corp (<a href=\"https://seekingalpha.com/symbol/NVDA\" title=\"NVIDIA Corporation\">NVDA</a>)</td> <td>6.52</td> </tr> <tr> <td>Amazon (<a href=\"https://seekingalpha.com/symbol/AMZN\" title=\"Amazon.com, Inc.\">AMZN</a>)</td> <td>4.49</td> </tr> <tr> <td>Alphabet Inc Class A (<a href=\"https://seekingalpha.com/symbol/GOOG\" title=\"Alphabet Inc.\">GOOG</a>)(<a href=\"https://seekingalpha.com/symbol/GOOGL\" title=\"Alphabet Inc.\">GOOGL</a>)</td> <td>2.81</td> </tr> <tr> <td>Meta Platforms Inc Class A (<a href=\"https://seekingalpha.com/symbol/META\" title=\"Meta Platforms, Inc.\">META</a>)</td> <td>2.69</td> </tr> <tr> <td>Tesla Inc (<a href=\"https://seekingalpha.com/symbol/TSLA\" title=\"Tesla, Inc.\">TSLA</a>)</td> <td>1.87</td> </tr> <tr> <td>Alphabet</td> <td>1.72</td> </tr> <tr> <td>Visa Inc Class A (<a href=\"https://seekingalpha.com/symbol/V\" title=\"Visa Inc.\">V</a>)</td> <td>1.63</td> </tr> <tr> <td>Costco Wholesale Corp (<a href=\"https://seekingalpha.com/symbol/COST\" title=\"Costco Wholesale Corporation\">COST</a>)</td> <td>1.53</td> </tr> </table> <span data-intersection-boundary=\"end\"></span></span><button class=\"table-enlarge-button\"><svg viewbox=\"0 0 16 16\" xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/2000/svg\" class=\"table-enlarge-icon\"><path fill-rule=\"evenodd\" clip-rule=\"evenodd\" d=\"M16 11a5 5 0 0 1-5 5H5a5 5 0 0 1-5-5V5a5 5 0 0 1 5-5h6a5 5 0 0 1 5 5v6zm-4.5-2.5h2v-6h-6v2h4v4zm-9-1h2v4h4v2h-6v-6z\"></path></svg>Click to enlarge</button></span> <span class=\"table-responsive paywall-full-content\"><span class=\"table-scroll-wrapper\"><span data-intersection-boundary=\"start\"></span><table> <tr> <td><p><strong>Contributors</strong></p></td> <td><p><strong>Detractors</strong></p></td> </tr> <tr> <td><p>Certain insights provided support during the quarter. Growth-oriented measures helped to offset broader weakness in fundamentals, particularly following the election. An insight evaluating research spending across assets and text-based predictions of company sales growth benefited performance. Text-based insights gauging sentiment from broker reports and analyzing online search trends motivated a successful underweight exposure to real estate companies. Top-down macro insights identifying historically similar economic regimes to today correctly drove an underweight allocation to the consumer staples sector.</p></td> <td> <p>Security selection struggled as the market became more speculative following the election, with fundamental valuation and quality insights both challenged.</p> <p>Defensive quality measures with a preference for lower-volatility companies motivated unsuccessful stock selection in the industrials sector. Traditional valuation measures evaluating company sales relative to enterprise value struggled as security selection in the IT sector proved wrong-footed, with perceived artificial intelligence winners evolving. Following the election, measures gauging sentiment from retail positioning were weak in the financials sector.</p> </td> </tr> </table> <span data-intersection-boundary=\"end\"></span></span><button class=\"table-enlarge-button\"><svg viewbox=\"0 0 16 16\" xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/2000/svg\" class=\"table-enlarge-icon\"><path fill-rule=\"evenodd\" clip-rule=\"evenodd\" d=\"M16 11a5 5 0 0 1-5 5H5a5 5 0 0 1-5-5V5a5 5 0 0 1 5-5h6a5 5 0 0 1 5 5v6zm-4.5-2.5h2v-6h-6v2h4v4zm-9-1h2v4h4v2h-6v-6z\"></path></svg>Click to enlarge</button></span> <h2 class=\"paywall-full-content\">Further insight</h2> <p class=\"paywall-full-content\">Investor attention was primarily focused on the U.S. election, with equities responding well to the Republican gains. After struggling for direction in October, a strong “risk-on” rally continued in early December before fading. More speculative growth stocks, alongside cryptocurrencies, benefited the most, given their perceived exposure to the incoming policy agenda. While leadership broadened through November, small-cap stocks surged on deregulation and lower tax hopes, though the rally lost steam at year-end. This, in effect, reconcentrated markets to a handful of large-cap technology stocks, which ensured that U.S. equities outperformed their global counterparts. Notably, the performance of these longer duration (higher interest rate sensitivity) growth stocks ran against yield-curve steepening, as longer-dated yields rose despite the Federal Reserve rate cut in November.</p> <span class=\"table-responsive paywall-full-content\"><span class=\"table-scroll-wrapper\"><spa